  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Innovative monitoring and reporting for Sustainable Water quality of the Meghna River (ISWAM)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2022;	Short general project overviewThe project aims to demonstrate how innovative smartphone-based water quality testing and easy access to data can improve water quality management decisions. The long-term objective of this project is to contribute towards safe drinking water for 8 million citizens in Dhaka. The drinking water supply of Dhaka mainly comes from groundwater sources. However, population growth and increasing water demand and use leads to risks for the people and the environment of Dhaka and the surrounding area. DWASA is looking towards surface water as an alternative source of drinking water; however, to date, they are lacking data to make informed decisions concerning operational and management decisions and infrastructure development. The project location is the Meghna River near Dhaka. The project is complementary to the ADB project &#x201C;Strengthening Monitoring and Enforcement in the Meghna River for Dhaka&apos;s Sustainable Water Supply&#x201D;.&#x2022;	Project goals1. Piloting an innovative monitoring technology and approach for the collection of surface water quality data by local stakeholders;2. Developing a monitoring and reporting network to provide near-real time, quantitative water quality data to DoE and DWASA in order to raise awareness about water pollution and to stimulate data-driven decision-making;3. Strengthening the involvement and participation of local authorities in the sustainable management of the Meghna River, which is essential for future uptake and expansion; and4. Disseminating the results of the Meghna River case to professionals and stakeholders with interests in water quality.&#x2022;	Results of the project- Local communities are committed to preserve the environment and participate in measures to improve WQ. Citizen monitoring translated this commitment and willingness to participate into an actionable framework. This holds potential for future projects; and- DoE and DWASA are actively using the FEWS-Bangladesh system.What makes the technology, product, method or approach innovative?The innovative combination of mobile-based water quality data collection with easy-to-use data visualization is unique and will assist in both the policy and enforcement (DoE) and the operational planning and management (DWASA) of drinking water provision, contributing to water security.</narrative>
  </description>
